# Decomposition Module 6: Assembly Line Designer

Welcome to the final module of the decomposition curriculum. This one borrows from **manufacturing / industrial engineering**: Henry Ford broke complex car assembly into simple, repeatable stations. You'll apply the same thinking to software processes.

The core translations you'll be working with:

| Factory floor | Software |
|---|---|
| Specialized stations | Single-responsibility services |
| Standard interfaces | APIs / data contracts |
| Quality checkpoints | Validation & testing stages |
| Parallel production lines | Concurrent workflows |
| Inventory buffers | Queues / caches |
| Optimization metrics | Performance monitoring |

This is interactive — I'll give you a production goal, you design the line. Let's start.

---

## Challenge 1: User Registration Assembly Line

Right now registration is an "artisan workshop" — one giant function doing everything:

```
function registerUser(userData) {
    // validate input
    // check email already exists
    // hash password
    // create user record
    // send welcome email
    // auto-login
    // create default preferences
    // send analytics event
    // return success
}
```

**Your task:** Redesign this as an assembly line.

1. Which steps **must** run **sequentially** on the main line (order matters / later steps depend on earlier ones)?
2. Which steps can be split off into **parallel production lines** (fire-and-forget, don't block the response)?
3. Pick one station and tell me what its **quality checkpoint** would be.

Take your time and design it — then I'll give you feedback before we move to the order-processing plant.

 I'm moving into Module 6, the final module focused on assembly line design. Rather than lecturing, I'll present each challenge interactively and have the participant work through the problems—the first two challenges have most of the structure provided, while the third one requires them to design their own sections. Let me start by presenting the first challenge and asking them to engage with it.
